We are an interdisciplinary team of scientists who generate and research new ideas about the intergenerational and life course determinants of human health. We believe that scientists from various fields must work together to achieve more than incremental advancements in our current knowledge of psychiatry and society.     Daniel Antonius, PhD   Pamela Butler Kahn, PhD   Ronit Calderon-Margalit, MD, MPH   Moses Chao, PhD   David Freedman, PhD, ScM   Yechiel Friedlander, PhD   Raymond Goetz, PhD   Oded Gonen, PhD   Susan Harlap, MBBS   Thorsten Kranz, PhD       Mariana Lazar, PhD   Pesach Lichtenberg, MD   Orly Manor, PhD   Julie Walsh-Messinger, PhD   Mark Opler, PhD, MPH   Ora Paltiel, MD, MSc   Carlos Pato, MD, PhD   Mary Rosedale, PhD, PMHNP-BC, NEA-BC   Karen Rothman, BA         Daniel Antonius, PhD   Daniel Antonius, PhD, is a research scientist with InSPIRES, a faculty member at the University at Buffalo School of Medicine and Biomedical Sciences, and a forensic psychologist with the Erie County Forensic Mental Health Services. Dr. Antonius’ research focuses on neurobiological, behavioral, and societal factors that underlie emotions, aggression and impulsivity. He has published numerous journal articles, book chapters, and books on aggression, violence, emotions, mental illness, psychological assessment, forensic issues, psychometrics, and terrorism. He was previously the Co-Editor of the peer-refereed journal Behavioral Sciences of Terrorism and Political Aggression. Dr. Antonius is the recipient of several awards and grants, including from the Association for Threat Assessment Professionals, the International Society for Research on Aggression, and the American Psychological Foundation.   Pamela Butler Kahn, PhD   Dr. Pamela Kahn is an Associate Professor of Psychiatry at NYU School of Medicine. Her work has focused on impaired perceptual ability of patients with schizophrenia. Graduate students and post-docs in her lab utilize psychophysical, electrophysiological, and MRI techniques to study perceptual dysfunction. They have also developed an "assay" of magnocellular visual pathway dysfunction that enables us to assess NMDA-mediated impairments in signal amplification.   Ronit Calderon-Margalit, MD, MPH   Dr. Ronit Calderon-Margalit is a public health physician and lecturer in the Braun School of Public Health and Community Medicine at the Hebrew University. Dr. Calderon-Margalit serves as co-investigator on our collaborative Jerusalem Perinatal Cohort Study.   Moses Chao, PhD   Moses V. Chao received his BA degree from Pomona College and his PhD from UCLA in biochemistry. He is presently Professor of Cell Biology, Physiology & Neuroscience and Psychiatry at the NYU School of Medicine. His laboratory defined the genes encoding the NGF receptor and his research interests are in defining mechanisms used by trophic factors to change synaptic plasticity.  Neurotrophins are responsible for many actions in the nervous system, including cell differentiation and survival and higher order functions, such as anxiety, depression, drug addiction, obesity, pain and neurodegenerative disorders.     Chao served as Senior Editor for the Journal of Neuroscience for eleven years and is currently a member of the Scientific Advisory Boards for the Simons Foundation, Target ALS, the Pershing Square Sohn Cancer Prize, the European Brain Research Foundation, the Danish Research Institute of Translation Neuroscience, the Brain Prize Advisory Committee, the NY Stem Cell Foundation and St. Jude’s Children’s Research Hospital.  Chao was President of the Society for Neuroscience for 2012.  He is a Fellow of the AAAS and a recipient of a Zenith Award from the Alzheimer’s Association, a Jacob Javits Neuroscience Investigator Award and a Guggenheim Fellowship.    David Freedman, PhD, ScM   Dr. Freedman's research focuses on cognition across the life-span, particularly on early life and developmental risks for cognitive impairment and psychiatric illness. His research is focused on the deviations from the typical developmental trajectory in neuropsychiatric illnesses, both acquired and developmental, and the role of social and cultural context in the development and course of cognitive impairment, psychiatric illness and social functioning.    He also serves as a consultant to legal defense teams in capital trials, providing assistance on recognition of mental health symptoms, diagnostic and cognitive functioning testing and evaluation, including evaluating the reliability and validity of scientific and psychometric assessment tools; and more generally, guidance and supervision on the investigation of neurodevelopmental psychopathology and bio-psychosocial, multi-generational social history. He obtained his PhD, at Columbia University's Mailman School of Public Health in Epidemiology, having been awarded an NIMH Fellowship in Psychiatric Epidemiology. He obtained a ScM from the Harvard School of Public Health in 1999.   Yechiel Friedlander, PhD   Dr. Friedlander is a Professor in Genetic-Epidemiology at the Hebrew University-Hadassah School of Public Health, Jerusalem, Israel. He received his Ph.D. degree in Genetic Epidemiology in 1985 from the Hebrew University. In 2003 Dr. Friedlander was appointed as the incumbent of the Jerrold M. Michael Chair in Public Health at the Hebrew University Faculty of Medicine. During his academic carrier, Dr. Friedlander addressed many research questions in genetic and cardiovascular epidemiology. The topics of his research are characterized by a multi-dimensional approach and the hypotheses which are being tested include developmental, life-style and socio-behavioral factors on the one hand, biological components on the other, and the possible interactions between these factors. Dr. Friedlander has over 250 publications and served as a tutor to many graduate students for their master and PhD degrees.   Raymond Goetz, PhD   Raymond Goetz has a PhD in Experimental Psychology with additional training and vast experience in study design, data management and statistical analyses. He is a Research Scientist with the Division of Clinical Phenomenology at the New York State Psychiatric Institute, and an Assistant Professor with the Department of Psychiatry at Columbia University. He has co-authored more than 130 peer-reviewed papers in the areas of psychiatry and psychology, examining physiological, neuropsychological and clinical phenomenology in patient groups ranging from anxiety disorders to depression to schizophrenia and schizoaffective disorders. He has consulted with many research groups in the New York City area regarding data management and statistical issues. Dr. Goetz has served as the Data Manager for InSPIRES for many years.   Oded Gonen, PhD   Oded Gonen, PhD, is a Professor of Radiology at NYU School of Medicine. His research interests include Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy and its applications to cancer, neurodegenerative diseases and psychiatric disorders, and the development of MR-spectroscopy tools to support medical and biomedical research.   Susan Harlap, MBBS   Susan Harlap, MBBS, is an epidemiologist with expertise in reproduction, cancer and psychiatry. She obtained her medical degree from London University’s Royal Free Hospital School of Medicine and worked in private practice in inner-city London. She immigrated to Israel in 1967 and was on the faculty at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem for 22 years, teaching epidemiology, doing research in obstetrics and reproduction, working on the Jerusalem Perinatal Study and serving as a consultant or advisor to the World Health Organization. Since moving to the US in 1988, she has worked for Family Health International, the Alan Gutmacher Institute and Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, and held faculty positions at Cornell and at Columbia University’s Mailman School of Public Health. She is currently a professor of Epidemiology in the departments of Psychiatry, OBGYN and Environmental Medicine. She has written a book on the benefits and risks of different methods of birth control - and has published over 175 papers.   Thorsten Kranz, PhD   Thorsten Kranz, PhD is a post-doctoral researcher at NYU School of Medicine working under the mentorship of Dr. Moses Chao, an internationally recognized expert on neurotrophin signaling. Dr. Kranz has a strong educational background and experience in biochemistry beginning with his graduate thesis in neurobehavioral and psychiatric genetics. As a PhD candidate ('06), Dr. Kranz examined the biochemical characterization of the potassium chloride cotransporter 2 (KCC2) in the auditory brainstem of developing rats. For his dissertation, he focused on the genetic architecture of autism and schizophrenia in multiplex pedigree families, identifying a segregating part of chromosome 15q14 among families with accumulation of schizophrenia. He also performed a hypothesis-driven genetic association study in autism parent-child trios on the oxytocin receptor, which is the target receptor for the social bonding adapting neuropeptide oxytocin.   In collaboration with Dr. Dolores Malaspina, Dr. Kranz has begun to conduct a pilot project on sporadic schizophrenia cases and performed a targeted exome capture experiment of neurotrophin genes and other signaling genes, which harbored de novo mutations in an earlier study performed with parent child trios diagnosed with schizophrenia. They have identified several novel genetic variants in the neurotrophin receptor pathway and plan to biochemically characterize some of these mutations in order to understand their biological impact during neurodevelopment. Dr. Kranz further plans to perform whole exome sequencing of schizophrenia cases in order to replicate their previous findings and to identify potential other converging signaling pathways that might explain the etiology of specific traits observed in schizophrenia.   Mariana Lazar, PhD   Mariana Lazar is an Assistant Professor of Radiology at NYU School of Medicine. Her research interests include diffusion imaging, aging, white matter, working memory, multimodal image integration, and brain development and connectivity in neuropsychiatric and neurological diseases.    Pesach Lichtenberg, MD   Pesach Lichtenberg, MD, is a Clinical Associate Professor of Psychiatry at the Hebrew University in Jerusalem, and serves as Director of the Division of Men’s Psychiatry at Herzog Hospital. His research interests include schizophrenia, placebo treatment, and alternatives to psychiatric hospitalization. Dr. Lichtenberg serves as co-investigator on our collaborative Jerusalem Perinatal Cohort Study.   Orly Manor, PhD   Orly Manor received her PhD in Statistics from Stockholm University. Currently, Dr. Manor serves as Chairman of the Israel National Institute for Health Policy Research and Professor of Biostatistics at the Braun School of Public Health and Community Medicine of the Hebrew University-Hadassah Medical Organization in Jerusalem. Her research focuses include biostatistics and epidemiology applied to cardiovascular health and disease and clinical and genetic epidemiology as well as health inequalities, the developmental origin of adult disease and quality of care. Dr. Manor serves as co-investigator on our collaborative Jerusalem Perinatal Cohort Study.   Julie Walsh-Messinger, PhD   Julie Walsh-Messinger, PhD, is a clinical rater and collaborator for INSPIRES, and a clinical psychologist at the Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai Hospital. Her research interests are broadly focused on olfaction, negative symptoms and sexual dimorphisms in schizophrenia. She studied cognitive-affective processes and olfactory hedonics within schizophrenia for her dissertation research at Long Island University. Dr. Walsh-Messinger is currently completing her post-doctorate fellowship at the James J Peters VA Medical Center in the Bronx. She will soon join the Psychology faculty at the University of Dayton.    Mark Opler, PhD, MPH   Dr. Mark Opler's research focuses on the etiology, life course, and treatment of schizophrenia and other psychiatric disorder. His research has largely focused on the impact of paternal and prenatal chemical exposures on the risk of psychotic disorders.    Dr. Opler is a graduate of the NIMH-supported Psychiatric Epidemiology Training program and has also completed a post-doctoral fellowship in the Schizophrenia Research Training program in the Department of Psychiatry at Columbia University. He was formerly an Assistant Professor at NYU Medical Center in the Department of Psychiatry but has since returned to industry.    Ora Paltiel, MD, MSc   Ora Paltiel received her MD in Internal Medicine from McGill University Montreal, Canada followed by a fellowship in Hematology and Oncology. She also holds a Master’s Degree in Epidemiology and Biostatistics. Currently Dr. Paltiel serves as Senior Physician in the Department of Hematology at the Hadassah Medical Center and director of the IMPH Program at its School of Public Health. Much of her research has focused on Cancer Epidemiology in Israel, concentrating on a variety of risk factors, especially perinatal events and exposures. Dr. Paltiel serves as co-investigator on our collaborative Jerusalem Perinatal Cohort Study.   Carlos Pato, MD, PhD   Dr. Pato is a renowned clinician and researcher of neuropsychiatric genetics. He completed his residency in Psychiatry from Massachusetts General Hospital (1983-1986) followed by a Fellowship from the National Institute of Mental Health (1986-1987). He currently serves as Franz Alexander Chair and Professor of Psychiatry at Keck School of Medicine at the University of Southern California. Dr. Pato is the central PI of our collaborative Genomic Psychiatry Cohort Study, and leads investigation at the main study site at the University of Southern California.   Mary Rosedale, PhD, PMHNP-BC, NEA-BC   Mary Rosedale is an Assistant Professor at the NYU College of Nursing and holds an Associated Faculty Appointment with the Department of Psychiatry, NYU Medical Center. The focus of her research is on neurostimulation and women’s mental health and brain health across the life span.   She is particularly interested in epidemiology, risk factors, and women’s long term mental health clinical course and the use of brain stimulation methodologies for neuropsychiatric treatment. She is a board-certified psychiatric nurse practitioner and advanced level nursing executive. She has held executive level health care positions for more than a decade, published and presented nationally and internationally on topics including psychological distress of breast cancer survivors, nursing science as a key component of the clinical practice of brain stimulation therapies, and development and implementation of psychiatric home care. She has consulted to Israel’s Ministry of Health and Chilean Association of Schools of Nursing. As a member of the Institute for Social and Psychiatric Initiatives at NYU (InSPIRES), Dr. Rosedale's international nursing leadership is paving the way for the development of new nursing roles and international, interdisciplinary collaborations as well as important research initiatives.   Karen Rothman, BA   Karen Rothman received her B.A. in Psychology from Skidmore College ('14) and is currently working as a Research Coordinator for InSPIRES. Her research interests include intergenerational stress and the role of early life trauma in psychopathology. We are an interdisciplinary team of scientists who generate and research new ideas about the intergenerational and life course determinants of human health. We believe that scientists from various fields must work together to achieve more than incremental advancements in our current knowledge of psychiatry and society.     Daniel Antonius, PhD   Pamela Butler Kahn, PhD   Ronit Calderon-Margalit, MD, MPH   Moses Chao, PhD   David Freedman, PhD, ScM   Yechiel Friedlander, PhD   Raymond Goetz, PhD   Oded Gonen, PhD   Susan Harlap, MBBS   Thorsten Kranz, PhD       Mariana Lazar, PhD   Pesach Lichtenberg, MD   Orly Manor, PhD   Julie Walsh-Messinger, PhD   Mark Opler, PhD, MPH   Ora Paltiel, MD, MSc   Carlos Pato, MD, PhD   Mary Rosedale, PhD, PMHNP-BC, NEA-BC   Karen Rothman, BA         Daniel Antonius, PhD   Daniel Antonius, PhD, is a research scientist with InSPIRES, a faculty member at the University at Buffalo School of Medicine and Biomedical Sciences, and a forensic psychologist with the Erie County Forensic Mental Health Services. Dr. Antonius’ research focuses on neurobiological, behavioral, and societal factors that underlie emotions, aggression and impulsivity. He has published numerous journal articles, book chapters, and books on aggression, violence, emotions, mental illness, psychological assessment, forensic issues, psychometrics, and terrorism. He was previously the Co-Editor of the peer-refereed journal Behavioral Sciences of Terrorism and Political Aggression. Dr. Antonius is the recipient of several awards and grants, including from the Association for Threat Assessment Professionals, the International Society for Research on Aggression, and the American Psychological Foundation.   Pamela Butler Kahn, PhD   Dr. Pamela Kahn is an Associate Professor of Psychiatry at NYU School of Medicine. Her work has focused on impaired perceptual ability of patients with schizophrenia. Graduate students and post-docs in her lab utilize psychophysical, electrophysiological, and MRI techniques to study perceptual dysfunction. They have also developed an "assay" of magnocellular visual pathway dysfunction that enables us to assess NMDA-mediated impairments in signal amplification.   Ronit Calderon-Margalit, MD, MPH   Dr. Ronit Calderon-Margalit is a public health physician and lecturer in the Braun School of Public Health and Community Medicine at the Hebrew University. Dr. Calderon-Margalit serves as co-investigator on our collaborative Jerusalem Perinatal Cohort Study.   Moses Chao, PhD   Moses V. Chao received his BA degree from Pomona College and his PhD from UCLA in biochemistry. He is presently Professor of Cell Biology, Physiology & Neuroscience and Psychiatry at the NYU School of Medicine. His laboratory defined the genes encoding the NGF receptor and his research interests are in defining mechanisms used by trophic factors to change synaptic plasticity.  Neurotrophins are responsible for many actions in the nervous system, including cell differentiation and survival and higher order functions, such as anxiety, depression, drug addiction, obesity, pain and neurodegenerative disorders.     Chao served as Senior Editor for the Journal of Neuroscience for eleven years and is currently a member of the Scientific Advisory Boards for the Simons Foundation, Target ALS, the Pershing Square Sohn Cancer Prize, the European Brain Research Foundation, the Danish Research Institute of Translation Neuroscience, the Brain Prize Advisory Committee, the NY Stem Cell Foundation and St. Jude’s Children’s Research Hospital.  Chao was President of the Society for Neuroscience for 2012.  He is a Fellow of the AAAS and a recipient of a Zenith Award from the Alzheimer’s Association, a Jacob Javits Neuroscience Investigator Award and a Guggenheim Fellowship.    David Freedman, PhD, ScM   Dr. Freedman's research focuses on cognition across the life-span, particularly on early life and developmental risks for cognitive impairment and psychiatric illness. His research is focused on the deviations from the typical developmental trajectory in neuropsychiatric illnesses, both acquired and developmental, and the role of social and cultural context in the development and course of cognitive impairment, psychiatric illness and social functioning.    He also serves as a consultant to legal defense teams in capital trials, providing assistance on recognition of mental health symptoms, diagnostic and cognitive functioning testing and evaluation, including evaluating the reliability and validity of scientific and psychometric assessment tools; and more generally, guidance and supervision on the investigation of neurodevelopmental psychopathology and bio-psychosocial, multi-generational social history. He obtained his PhD, at Columbia University's Mailman School of Public Health in Epidemiology, having been awarded an NIMH Fellowship in Psychiatric Epidemiology. He obtained a ScM from the Harvard School of Public Health in 1999.   Yechiel Friedlander, PhD   Dr. Friedlander is a Professor in Genetic-Epidemiology at the Hebrew University-Hadassah School of Public Health, Jerusalem, Israel. He received his Ph.D. degree in Genetic Epidemiology in 1985 from the Hebrew University. In 2003 Dr. Friedlander was appointed as the incumbent of the Jerrold M. Michael Chair in Public Health at the Hebrew University Faculty of Medicine. During his academic carrier, Dr. Friedlander addressed many research questions in genetic and cardiovascular epidemiology. The topics of his research are characterized by a multi-dimensional approach and the hypotheses which are being tested include developmental, life-style and socio-behavioral factors on the one hand, biological components on the other, and the possible interactions between these factors. Dr. Friedlander has over 250 publications and served as a tutor to many graduate students for their master and PhD degrees.   Raymond Goetz, PhD   Raymond Goetz has a PhD in Experimental Psychology with additional training and vast experience in study design, data management and statistical analyses. He is a Research Scientist with the Division of Clinical Phenomenology at the New York State Psychiatric Institute, and an Assistant Professor with the Department of Psychiatry at Columbia University. He has co-authored more than 130 peer-reviewed papers in the areas of psychiatry and psychology, examining physiological, neuropsychological and clinical phenomenology in patient groups ranging from anxiety disorders to depression to schizophrenia and schizoaffective disorders. He has consulted with many research groups in the New York City area regarding data management and statistical issues. Dr. Goetz has served as the Data Manager for InSPIRES for many years.   Oded Gonen, PhD   Oded Gonen, PhD, is a Professor of Radiology at NYU School of Medicine. His research interests include Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy and its applications to cancer, neurodegenerative diseases and psychiatric disorders, and the development of MR-spectroscopy tools to support medical and biomedical research.   Susan Harlap, MBBS   Susan Harlap, MBBS, is an epidemiologist with expertise in reproduction, cancer and psychiatry. She obtained her medical degree from London University’s Royal Free Hospital School of Medicine and worked in private practice in inner-city London. She immigrated to Israel in 1967 and was on the faculty at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem for 22 years, teaching epidemiology, doing research in obstetrics and reproduction, working on the Jerusalem Perinatal Study and serving as a consultant or advisor to the World Health Organization. Since moving to the US in 1988, she has worked for Family Health International, the Alan Gutmacher Institute and Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, and held faculty positions at Cornell and at Columbia University’s Mailman School of Public Health. She is currently a professor of Epidemiology in the departments of Psychiatry, OBGYN and Environmental Medicine. She has written a book on the benefits and risks of different methods of birth control - and has published over 175 papers.   Thorsten Kranz, PhD   Thorsten Kranz, PhD is a post-doctoral researcher at NYU School of Medicine working under the mentorship of Dr. Moses Chao, an internationally recognized expert on neurotrophin signaling. Dr. Kranz has a strong educational background and experience in biochemistry beginning with his graduate thesis in neurobehavioral and psychiatric genetics. As a PhD candidate ('06), Dr. Kranz examined the biochemical characterization of the potassium chloride cotransporter 2 (KCC2) in the auditory brainstem of developing rats. For his dissertation, he focused on the genetic architecture of autism and schizophrenia in multiplex pedigree families, identifying a segregating part of chromosome 15q14 among families with accumulation of schizophrenia. He also performed a hypothesis-driven genetic association study in autism parent-child trios on the oxytocin receptor, which is the target receptor for the social bonding adapting neuropeptide oxytocin.   In collaboration with Dr. Dolores Malaspina, Dr. Kranz has begun to conduct a pilot project on sporadic schizophrenia cases and performed a targeted exome capture experiment of neurotrophin genes and other signaling genes, which harbored de novo mutations in an earlier study performed with parent child trios diagnosed with schizophrenia. They have identified several novel genetic variants in the neurotrophin receptor pathway and plan to biochemically characterize some of these mutations in order to understand their biological impact during neurodevelopment. Dr. Kranz further plans to perform whole exome sequencing of schizophrenia cases in order to replicate their previous findings and to identify potential other converging signaling pathways that might explain the etiology of specific traits observed in schizophrenia.   Mariana Lazar, PhD   Mariana Lazar is an Assistant Professor of Radiology at NYU School of Medicine. Her research interests include diffusion imaging, aging, white matter, working memory, multimodal image integration, and brain development and connectivity in neuropsychiatric and neurological diseases.    Pesach Lichtenberg, MD   Pesach Lichtenberg, MD, is a Clinical Associate Professor of Psychiatry at the Hebrew University in Jerusalem, and serves as Director of the Division of Men’s Psychiatry at Herzog Hospital. His research interests include schizophrenia, placebo treatment, and alternatives to psychiatric hospitalization. Dr. Lichtenberg serves as co-investigator on our collaborative Jerusalem Perinatal Cohort Study.   Orly Manor, PhD   Orly Manor received her PhD in Statistics from Stockholm University. Currently, Dr. Manor serves as Chairman of the Israel National Institute for Health Policy Research and Professor of Biostatistics at the Braun School of Public Health and Community Medicine of the Hebrew University-Hadassah Medical Organization in Jerusalem. Her research focuses include biostatistics and epidemiology applied to cardiovascular health and disease and clinical and genetic epidemiology as well as health inequalities, the developmental origin of adult disease and quality of care. Dr. Manor serves as co-investigator on our collaborative Jerusalem Perinatal Cohort Study.   Julie Walsh-Messinger, PhD   Julie Walsh-Messinger, PhD, is a clinical rater and collaborator for INSPIRES, and a clinical psychologist at the Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai Hospital. Her research interests are broadly focused on olfaction, negative symptoms and sexual dimorphisms in schizophrenia. She studied cognitive-affective processes and olfactory hedonics within schizophrenia for her dissertation research at Long Island University. Dr. Walsh-Messinger is currently completing her post-doctorate fellowship at the James J Peters VA Medical Center in the Bronx. She will soon join the Psychology faculty at the University of Dayton.    Mark Opler, PhD, MPH   Dr. Mark Opler's research focuses on the etiology, life course, and treatment of schizophrenia and other psychiatric disorder. His research has largely focused on the impact of paternal and prenatal chemical exposures on the risk of psychotic disorders.    Dr. Opler is a graduate of the NIMH-supported Psychiatric Epidemiology Training program and has also completed a post-doctoral fellowship in the Schizophrenia Research Training program in the Department of Psychiatry at Columbia University. He was formerly an Assistant Professor at NYU Medical Center in the Department of Psychiatry but has since returned to industry.    Ora Paltiel, MD, MSc   Ora Paltiel received her MD in Internal Medicine from McGill University Montreal, Canada followed by a fellowship in Hematology and Oncology. She also holds a Master’s Degree in Epidemiology and Biostatistics. Currently Dr. Paltiel serves as Senior Physician in the Department of Hematology at the Hadassah Medical Center and director of the IMPH Program at its School of Public Health. Much of her research has focused on Cancer Epidemiology in Israel, concentrating on a variety of risk factors, especially perinatal events and exposures. Dr. Paltiel serves as co-investigator on our collaborative Jerusalem Perinatal Cohort Study.   Carlos Pato, MD, PhD   Dr. Pato is a renowned clinician and researcher of neuropsychiatric genetics. He completed his residency in Psychiatry from Massachusetts General Hospital (1983-1986) followed by a Fellowship from the National Institute of Mental Health (1986-1987). He currently serves as Franz Alexander Chair and Professor of Psychiatry at Keck School of Medicine at the University of Southern California. Dr. Pato is the central PI of our collaborative Genomic Psychiatry Cohort Study, and leads investigation at the main study site at the University of Southern California.   Mary Rosedale, PhD, PMHNP-BC, NEA-BC   Mary Rosedale is an Assistant Professor at the NYU College of Nursing and holds an Associated Faculty Appointment with the Department of Psychiatry, NYU Medical Center. The focus of her research is on neurostimulation and women’s mental health and brain health across the life span.   She is particularly interested in epidemiology, risk factors, and women’s long term mental health clinical course and the use of brain stimulation methodologies for neuropsychiatric treatment. She is a board-certified psychiatric nurse practitioner and advanced level nursing executive. She has held executive level health care positions for more than a decade, published and presented nationally and internationally on topics including psychological distress of breast cancer survivors, nursing science as a key component of the clinical practice of brain stimulation therapies, and development and implementation of psychiatric home care. She has consulted to Israel’s Ministry of Health and Chilean Association of Schools of Nursing. As a member of the Institute for Social and Psychiatric Initiatives at NYU (InSPIRES), Dr. Rosedale's international nursing leadership is paving the way for the development of new nursing roles and international, interdisciplinary collaborations as well as important research initiatives.   Karen Rothman, BA   Karen Rothman received her B.A. in Psychology from Skidmore College ('14) and is currently working as a Research Coordinator for InSPIRES. Her research interests include intergenerational stress and the role of early life trauma in psychopathology.                                                      Jerome C. Wakefield    University Professor; Professor of Social Work; Professor of the Conceptual Foundations of Psychiatry, NYU School of Medicine; Affiliate Faculty, InSPIRES (Institute for Social and Psychiatric Initiatives: Research, Education and Service), Department of Psychiatry, NYU School of Medicine; Affiliate Faculty, NYU Center for Bioethics; Affiliate Faculty, NYU Center for Ancient Studies; Honorary Faculty, Institute for Psychoanalytic Education, NYU Medical Center, Director, Clinical Theory in Paris Program, NYU    BA, MA, MSW, PhD, DSW    jerome.wakefield@nyu.edu    (212) 998-5934                 Curriculum Vitae                              Areas of Expertise       Conceptual foundations of clinical theory, philosophy of psychopathology, psychiatric epidemiology of depression, integrative clinical theory, Freud studies                         Biography     Jerome C. Wakefield, DSW, PhD, has been University Professor and professor in the Silver School of Social Work at New York University since 2003. Prior to coming to NYU, he held faculty positions at University of Chicago, Columbia University, and Rutgers University. His clinical training and experience have been within the mental health field and were integrative, including psychodynamic, cognitive, behavioral, and family training, with work in agencies as well as private practice; he is currently a licensed clinical social worker in New Jersey.   His scholarly specialty is the conceptual foundations of clinical theory. He is the author of over 200 publications appearing in journals and books in psychology, philosophy, psychiatry, psychoanalysis, and social work, dealing with issues at the intersection of philosophy and the mental health professions. Much of his recent work has concerned the concept of mental disorder, especially how normal negative responses to a problematic social environment can be distinguished from mental disorder and how DSM diagnostic criteria fail to adequately draw this distinction. Rejecting both the anti-psychiatric critique that holds that there is no such thing as mental disorder other than as a label for socially disvalued conditions, and the standard psychiatric position that any well-defined syndromal set of symptoms can define a disorder, Dr. Wakefield argues for a middle ground position in which the concept of a physical or mental medical disorder is a hybrid value and scientific concept requiring both harm, assessed according to social values, and dysfunction, anchored in facts about evolutionary design. Unlike the anti-psychiatric view, Dr. Wakefield’s "harmful dysfunction" analysis offers a position from which to mount meaningful and constructive criticism of standard psychiatric diagnostic criteria based on assumptions about disorder that, he argues, lie at the foundation of psychiatry itself. This work has been widely recognized. For example, in 1995, NIMH held a conference of leading researchers on conduct disorder devoted to exploring the implications of Dr. Wakefield's views for that field. In 1999, a special issue of the Journal of Abnormal Psychology was devoted to his views; his analysis is widely cited in abnormal psychology and introductory psychology textbooks; and many articles have appeared in journals devoted to analyzing and critiquing his views.     In addition to his work on mental disorder, Dr. Wakefield is known for his analysis of the profession of social work as a field properly concerned with "minimal distributive justice," a view on which he has elaborated in a series of articles on the conceptual foundations of social work. In this work, using John Rawls's theory of justice as a framework, Dr. Wakefield attempts to integrate the traditional justice-oriented essential mission of social work with the profession's clinical focus via an account of “psychological justice,” the psychological features individuals need in order to participate effectively in our society given its special values and opportunities. Dr. Wakefield has also made substantial contributions to the conceptual foundations of psychoanalysis, especially in a series of articles excavating the linkages between Freud's approach to the mind and current cognitive science approaches. Recent publications include critiques of some aspects of the "relational" approach to the mind in psychoanalysis, and a series of articles examining Freud’s case history of “Little Hans.” Other topics of his scholarship range from an elaboration of a Platonic version of Erikson's concept of generativity to the implications of Continental phenomenology for the psychoanalysis of personality disorders.   Current projects include a series of articles recently published or in preparation using large psychiatric epidemiological data sets to explore issues of diagnostic validity for mental disorders, particularly depression and substance dependence. He is completing a two-volume analysis of Freud’s case of Little Hans from philosophy-of-science and Foucaultian perspectives. He is also working on a book on Freud and philosophy of mind.   Dr. Wakefield earned his BA from Queens College (CUNY), with concentrations in philosophy, psychology, and mathematics. He holds an MSW in clinical social work, an MA in mathematics with a specialization in logic and methodology of science (George Kelley, Thesis Chair: Evolution of the theory of proportions in ancient Greek mathematics), and two doctoral degrees, one in social welfare (Eileen Gambrill and William Runyan, Dissertation Co-Chairs: Psychosexual disorders: Studies in the role of psychotherapeutic ideology in diagnosis and treatment), and the other in philosophy (John Searle, Dissertation Chair: Do unconscious mental states exist?: Freud, Searle, and the conceptual foundations of cognitive science), all from U C Berkeley.   Dr. Wakefield has held post-doctoral fellowships in women's studies at Brown University’s Pembroke Center for Teaching and Research on Women, where he worked on the history of medical diagnoses of sexual dysfunction and the sex biases inherent in such diagnoses; cognitive science at University of California at Berkeley, where he worked on integrating psychodynamic theory with cognitive science; and mental health services research at Rutgers, where he worked on the validity of diagnostic criteria for mental disorder. He serves on the National Advisory Board of the Society for the Exploration of Psychotherapy Integration, is a founding fellow of the Council for Scientific Medicine and Mental Health, is an elected member of the Rapaport-Klein Study Group in Ego Psychology, and is a lecturer in psychiatry (Biometrics Unit) at Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons. He has served on the editorial boards of Social Work Research and Research on Social Work Practice , is currently on the editorial board of Psicoterapia e scienze umane , and is a regular peer reviewer for leading journals in social work, philosophy, psychiatry, and psychology.   In April 2007, Dr. Wakefield was the lead author of a paper published in the Archives of General Psychiatry , “ Extending the Bereavement Exclusion for Major Depression to Other Losses: Evidence From the National Comorbidity Survey .” The article described ways that symptoms of intense sadness due to a variety of losses may resemble those of major depressive disorder (MDD), but may not indicate a mental disorder. The publication, which challenged conventional thinking on the manifestations of depression, also gained national and international coverage in outlets that included The Washington Post , The San Francisco Chronicle , The New York Times , BBC World News , The Boston Globe , National Public Radio , and ABC World News with Charles Gibson . His subsequent work on depression, grief, and sadness and the boundary between normal and disordered emotions has continued to draw media attention, including an appearance on NBC Nightly News with Brian Williams.    A book by Wakefield on this topic, written with Rutgers sociologist Allan Horwitz and titled The Loss of Sadness: How Psychiatry Transformed Normal Sorrow into Depressive Disorder was published in 2007 by Oxford University Press. This book won Association of American Publishers’ award as the Best Psychology Book of 2007. Three conferences were held in Paris in summer 2010 on themes in Dr. Wakefield's work on depression. A second book with coauthor Horwitz, All We Have to Fear: Psychiatry’s Transformation of Natural Anxieties into Mental Disorders, was published by Oxford University Press in 2012.
